<subSubSection box="[199,1273,871,897]" pageId="1" pageNumber="584" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,798,1905]" box="[199,1273,871,897]" pageId="1" pageNumber="584">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,871,897]" pageId="1" pageNumber="584">Etymology.</emphasis>
Named after the Rhodope Mountains (
<collectingCountry box="[771,873,871,897]" name="Bulgaria" pageId="1" pageNumber="584">Bulgaria</collectingCountry>
), where the 
<typeStatus box="[1009,1107,871,897]" pageId="1" pageNumber="584">holotype</typeStatus>
was collected.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="584" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,798,1905]" pageId="1" pageNumber="584">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,322,906,932]" pageId="1" pageNumber="584">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
The male is morphologically similar to those of 
<taxonomicName authority="Lazarov, 2005" authorityName="Lazarov" authorityYear="2005" box="[863,1293,906,933]" class="Arachnida" family="Nemesiidae" genus="Brachythele" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="1" pageNumber="584" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="langourovi">
<emphasis box="[863,1127,907,933]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="584">Brachythele langourovi</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Lazarov, S. P." box="[1133,1293,906,933]" pageId="1" pageNumber="584" pagination="189 - 193" refId="ref3680" refString="Lazarov, S. P. (2005) A new spider species from Bulgaria, Brachythele langourovi sp. n. (Araneae, Nemesiidae). Revue Suisse de Zoologie, 112 (1), 189 - 193. https: // doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. part. 80294" type="journal article" year="2005">Lazarov, 2005</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Zonstein 2007" authorityName="Zonstein" authorityYear="2007" class="Arachnida" family="Nemesiidae" genus="Brachythele" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="1" pageNumber="584" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bentzieni">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="584">Brachythele bentzieni</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Zonstein, S. L." box="[319,482,943,969]" pageId="1" pageNumber="584" pagination="15 - 17" refId="ref4063" refString="Zonstein, S. L. (2007) A new species of the mygalomorph spider genus Brachythele Ausserer, 1871 (Aranei: Nemesiidae) from Greece. Arthropoda Selecta, 16, 15 - 17." type="journal article" year="2007">Zonstein 2007</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, in the presence of an embolic keel (
<figureCitation box="[883,984,943,969]" captionStart="FIGURES 7–12" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1916,1940]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,617,1893]" captionTargetId="figure-145@3.[151,1436,617,1893]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 7–12. Brachythele rhodopensis sp. n., holotype male, palp (7–9) and Brachythele langourovi, paratype, male, palp (10–12). 7, 10 prolateral; 8, 11 ventral; 9, 12 retrolateral. Scale 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6786155" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6786155/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="584">Figs 7–8</figureCitation>
). It can be distinguished by (1) the shape of the keel being more massive than in the other 2 species, and (2) the shape of the embolic portion—stout, curved (
<figureCitation box="[159,260,1015,1041]" captionStart="FIGURES 7–12" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1916,1940]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,617,1893]" captionTargetId="figure-145@3.[151,1436,617,1893]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 7–12. Brachythele rhodopensis sp. n., holotype male, palp (7–9) and Brachythele langourovi, paratype, male, palp (10–12). 7, 10 prolateral; 8, 11 ventral; 9, 12 retrolateral. Scale 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6786155" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6786155/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="584">Figs 7–9</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[271,344,1014,1041]" captionStart="FIGURES 13–15" captionStartId="4.[151,264,959,983]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,273,935]" captionTargetId="figure-52@4.[151,1436,272,935]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 13–15. Brachythele rhodopensis sp. n., holotype male, palp. 13 prolateral; 14 ventral; 15 retrolateral. T—tegulum; E—embolus; K—embolic keel. Scale 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6786159" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6786159/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="584">13–15</figureCitation>
), whereas, in 
<emphasis box="[499,658,1015,1041]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="584">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lazarov" authorityYear="2005" box="[499,655,1015,1041]" class="Arachnida" family="Nemesiidae" genus="Brachythele" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="1" pageNumber="584" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="langourovi">B. langourovi</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
it is curved but thinner (
<figureCitation box="[933,1061,1015,1041]" captionStart="FIGURES 7–12" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1916,1940]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,617,1893]" captionTargetId="figure-145@3.[151,1436,617,1893]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 7–12. Brachythele rhodopensis sp. n., holotype male, palp (7–9) and Brachythele langourovi, paratype, male, palp (10–12). 7, 10 prolateral; 8, 11 ventral; 9, 12 retrolateral. Scale 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6786155" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6786155/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="584">Figs 10–12</figureCitation>
) and, in 
<emphasis box="[1158,1297,1015,1041]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="584">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Zonstein" authorityYear="2007" box="[1158,1293,1015,1041]" class="Arachnida" family="Nemesiidae" genus="Brachythele" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="1" pageNumber="584" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bentzieni">B. bentzieni</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
it is straight (
<figureCitation box="[159,290,1051,1077]" captionStart="FIGURES 26–27" captionStartId="7.[151,264,1657,1681]" captionTargetBox="[151,1427,781,1634]" captionTargetId="figure-286@7.[151,1436,777,1634]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURES 26–27. Brachythele bentzieni, male palp. 26 ventral; 27 retrolateral. Scale 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6786167" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6786167/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="584">Figs 26–27</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="584" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,798,1905]" pageId="1" pageNumber="584">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,345,1086,1112]" pageId="1" pageNumber="584">Description.</emphasis>
(
<typeStatus box="[361,467,1087,1113]" pageId="1" pageNumber="584">Holotype</typeStatus>
male). Measurements: Total length 12.76; carapace length 6.30, width 4.70; sternum length 3.07, width 2.25; labium length 0.64; maxilla length 2.02; abdomen length 6.46, width 3.25; PMS length 0.62; PLS length 2.10. Palp. Femur length 2.31, patella length 1.16, tibia length 1.85, cymbium length 0.86, bulbus length 1.21. Leg measurements: I—15.45 (3.90, 2.84, 2.79, 3.35, 2.57), II—14.18 (4.09,7 2.52, 2.70, 2.89, 1.98), III—14.99 (3.94, 2.30, 2.54, 3.56, 2.65), IV—18.73 (4.16, 2.91, 4.22, 4.74, 2.70). Eyes’ diameters: ALE 0.22, AME 0.18, PLE 0.18, PME 0.175. Eyes’ interdistances: AME–AME 0.15, AME–ALE 0.11, ALE–PLE 0.10, PME–PME 0.39, PME–PLE 0.10.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,798,1905]" pageId="1" pageNumber="584">
Color (
<figureCitation box="[278,344,1339,1365]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–6" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[180,1404,181,1918]" captionTargetId="figure-28@2.[180,1406,181,1919]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–6. Brachythele rhodopensis sp. n., holotype male. 1 habitus, dorsal; 2 carapace; 3 sternum; 4 spinnerets, ventral; 5 tibia I, ventral; 6 tibia I, lateral. Scale 2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6786153" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6786153/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="584">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
). Carapace brown, with darker margins (
<figureCitation box="[804,905,1339,1365]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–6" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[180,1404,181,1918]" captionTargetId="figure-28@2.[180,1406,181,1919]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–6. Brachythele rhodopensis sp. n., holotype male. 1 habitus, dorsal; 2 carapace; 3 sternum; 4 spinnerets, ventral; 5 tibia I, ventral; 6 tibia I, lateral. Scale 2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6786153" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6786153/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="584">Figs 1–2</figureCitation>
). Legs more or less the same color as carapace. Sternum and coxae yellow-brown, coxae lighter ventrally. Sternal sigilla small and rounded, the posterior pair well visible, the other 2 much lighter (
<figureCitation box="[523,585,1411,1437]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–6" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[180,1404,181,1918]" captionTargetId="figure-28@2.[180,1406,181,1919]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–6. Brachythele rhodopensis sp. n., holotype male. 1 habitus, dorsal; 2 carapace; 3 sternum; 4 spinnerets, ventral; 5 tibia I, ventral; 6 tibia I, lateral. Scale 2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6786153" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6786153/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="584">Fig 3</figureCitation>
). Chelicerae dark brown. Abdomen beige with darker brownish pattern (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURES 1–6" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[180,1404,181,1918]" captionTargetId="figure-28@2.[180,1406,181,1919]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–6. Brachythele rhodopensis sp. n., holotype male. 1 habitus, dorsal; 2 carapace; 3 sternum; 4 spinnerets, ventral; 5 tibia I, ventral; 6 tibia I, lateral. Scale 2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6786153" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6786153/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="584">Fig 1</figureCitation>
). Spinnerets light beige (
<figureCitation box="[447,510,1447,1473]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–6" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[180,1404,181,1918]" captionTargetId="figure-28@2.[180,1406,181,1919]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–6. Brachythele rhodopensis sp. n., holotype male. 1 habitus, dorsal; 2 carapace; 3 sternum; 4 spinnerets, ventral; 5 tibia I, ventral; 6 tibia I, lateral. Scale 2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6786153" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6786153/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="584">Fig 4</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,798,1905]" pageId="1" pageNumber="584">
Eyes. Eye region darker than surrounding dorsal surface of carapace, elevated. Eyes compact. Anterior eye row procurved, posterior one almost straight (as seen from dorsal side, 
<figureCitation box="[898,998,1519,1545]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–6" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[180,1404,181,1918]" captionTargetId="figure-28@2.[180,1406,181,1919]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–6. Brachythele rhodopensis sp. n., holotype male. 1 habitus, dorsal; 2 carapace; 3 sternum; 4 spinnerets, ventral; 5 tibia I, ventral; 6 tibia I, lateral. Scale 2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6786153" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6786153/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="584">Figs 1–2</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,798,1905]" pageId="1" pageNumber="584">
Other somatic characters. Carapace dorsally covered with fine setae. Fovea visible, deep, recurved. Chelicerae with 8 promarginal teeth, dorsally covered with long, weak, dense setae. Maxillae with many small prolateral cuspules on basal part (
<figureCitation box="[376,438,1627,1653]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–6" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[180,1404,181,1918]" captionTargetId="figure-28@2.[180,1406,181,1919]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–6. Brachythele rhodopensis sp. n., holotype male. 1 habitus, dorsal; 2 carapace; 3 sternum; 4 spinnerets, ventral; 5 tibia I, ventral; 6 tibia I, lateral. Scale 2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6786153" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6786153/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="584">Fig 3</figureCitation>
). Tibia I with distal spur bearing 2 strong spines (
<figureCitation box="[996,1099,1626,1653]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–6" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[180,1404,181,1918]" captionTargetId="figure-28@2.[180,1406,181,1919]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–6. Brachythele rhodopensis sp. n., holotype male. 1 habitus, dorsal; 2 carapace; 3 sternum; 4 spinnerets, ventral; 5 tibia I, ventral; 6 tibia I, lateral. Scale 2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6786153" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6786153/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="584">Figs 5–6</figureCitation>
). Scopula: distal on metatarsi, and entire on tarsi I–II; apical on tarsi III–IV. Trichobothria in 2 rows of 7–10 on tibiae and 9–11 on metatarsi. Paired claws with 7 teeth. PMS medium-sized; apical segment of PLS triangular.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,798,1905]" pageId="1" pageNumber="584">
Palp (
<figureCitation box="[265,367,1735,1761]" captionStart="FIGURES 7–12" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1916,1940]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,617,1893]" captionTargetId="figure-145@3.[151,1436,617,1893]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 7–12. Brachythele rhodopensis sp. n., holotype male, palp (7–9) and Brachythele langourovi, paratype, male, palp (10–12). 7, 10 prolateral; 8, 11 ventral; 9, 12 retrolateral. Scale 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6786155" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6786155/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="584">Figs 7–9</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[379,453,1734,1761]" captionStart="FIGURES 13–15" captionStartId="4.[151,264,959,983]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,273,935]" captionTargetId="figure-52@4.[151,1436,272,935]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 13–15. Brachythele rhodopensis sp. n., holotype male, palp. 13 prolateral; 14 ventral; 15 retrolateral. T—tegulum; E—embolus; K—embolic keel. Scale 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6786159" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6786159/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="584">13–15</figureCitation>
). Femur, patella, and cymbium spineless. Tibia with 2 long dorsal spines. Bulbus pearshaped; apical part protruding, massive in 2/3 of its length; embolic portion narrow, twisted, with a small tubercle distally.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,798,1905]" box="[199,414,1843,1869]" pageId="1" pageNumber="584">Female. Unknown.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[199,1419,1878,1905]" pageId="1" pageNumber="584" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,798,1905]" box="[199,1419,1878,1905]" pageId="1" pageNumber="584">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,353,1878,1904]" pageId="1" pageNumber="584">Distribution.</emphasis>
The species is known only from the 
<typeStatus box="[766,814,1879,1905]" pageId="1" pageNumber="584">type</typeStatus>
locality in the Eastern Rhodope Mountains, 
<collectingCountry box="[1315,1415,1879,1905]" name="Bulgaria" pageId="1" pageNumber="584">Bulgaria</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
